<paragraph id="4A185420961A456C5A9BFA39FC56F9B6" blockId="10.[166,1225,1122,1853]" lastBlockId="11.[174,1233,1415,1857]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="248" pageId="10" pageNumber="247">
Diagnosis. Both sexes of 
<taxonomicName id="8DA72FA3961A456D585EFA38FD3DFA6B" baseAuthorityName="Fallen" baseAuthorityYear="1817" box="[542,692,1506,1532]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pelecocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scaevoides">
<emphasis id="78D38832961A456D585EFA38FD3DFA6B" box="[542,692,1506,1532]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="247">P. scaevoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similar to 
<taxonomicName id="8DA72FA3961A456D5922FA38FB20FA6B" authority="(Collin, 1940)" baseAuthorityName="Collin" baseAuthorityYear="1940" box="[866,1193,1506,1532]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pelecocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caledonica">
<emphasis id="78D38832961A456D5922FA38FC72FA6B" box="[866,1019,1506,1532]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="247">P. caledonica</emphasis>
(Collin, 1940)
</taxonomicName>
in sharingthe following characters: anterodorsal portion of anepisternum without pile or setae, at most with thick microtrichia; frons, at the level of the antennal sockets, narrower than the width of an eye at the same level (
<figureCitation id="D29C48A5961A456D58D3F999FC85F9CB" box="[659,780,1602,1628]" captionStart="Figs 36–41" captionStartId="11.[174,213,1305,1327]" captionTargetBox="[204,1202,174,1283]" captionTargetId="figure-230@11.[204,1202,174,1283]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 36–41. Pelecocera (Chamaesyrphus) scaevoides: 36 — male habitus, dorsal view; 37 — male habitus, lateral view; 38 — male head and thorax, lateral view; 39 — male head, anterolateral view; 40 — male head, frontal view; 41 — female head, frontal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6455542" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6455542/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="247">figs 40, 41</figureCitation>
); propleural and mesopleural sclerites entirely covered in grey microtrichia (
<figureCitation id="D29C48A5961A456D5827F9B9FD3AF9EB" box="[615,691,1634,1660]" captionStart="Figs 36–41" captionStartId="11.[174,213,1305,1327]" captionTargetBox="[204,1202,174,1283]" captionTargetId="figure-230@11.[204,1202,174,1283]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 36–41. Pelecocera (Chamaesyrphus) scaevoides: 36 — male habitus, dorsal view; 37 — male habitus, lateral view; 38 — male head and thorax, lateral view; 39 — male head, anterolateral view; 40 — male head, frontal view; 41 — female head, frontal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6455542" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6455542/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="247">fig. 38</figureCitation>
); lateral arms of the lunule (extending round the dorsal edge of the antennal sockets) entirely shining, or entire lunule shining. From the male 
<taxonomicName id="8DA72FA3961A456D5AA5F978FEF4F92B" baseAuthorityName="Collin" baseAuthorityYear="1940" box="[229,381,1698,1724]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pelecocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caledonica">
<emphasis id="78D38832961A456D5AA5F978FEF4F92B" box="[229,381,1698,1724]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="247">P. caledonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the 
<emphasis id="78D38832961A456D5BEEF979FE60F92B" bold="true" box="[430,489,1698,1724]" pageId="10" pageNumber="247">male</emphasis>
of 
<taxonomicName id="8DA72FA3961A456D584EF978FD2BF92B" baseAuthorityName="Fallen" baseAuthorityYear="1817" box="[526,674,1698,1724]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pelecocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scaevoides">
<emphasis id="78D38832961A456D584EF978FD2BF92B" box="[526,674,1698,1724]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="247">P. scaevoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs by: face entirely covered in microtrichia (
<figureCitation id="D29C48A5961A456D5AEEF919FEADF94B" box="[174,292,1730,1756]" captionStart="Figs 36–41" captionStartId="11.[174,213,1305,1327]" captionTargetBox="[204,1202,174,1283]" captionTargetId="figure-230@11.[204,1202,174,1283]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 36–41. Pelecocera (Chamaesyrphus) scaevoides: 36 — male habitus, dorsal view; 37 — male habitus, lateral view; 38 — male head and thorax, lateral view; 39 — male head, anterolateral view; 40 — male head, frontal view; 41 — female head, frontal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6455542" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6455542/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="247">figs 39, 40</figureCitation>
) (in 
<taxonomicName id="8DA72FA3961A456D5B1AF918FE79F94B" baseAuthorityName="Collin" baseAuthorityYear="1940" box="[346,496,1730,1756]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pelecocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caledonica">
<emphasis id="78D38832961A456D5B1AF918FE79F94B" box="[346,496,1730,1756]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="247">P. caledonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, face with median black vitta shining); the length of postocular orbits is dorsally, at the inner end of the eye, shorter than a posterior ocellus (in 
<taxonomicName id="8DA72FA3961A456D5E32F938FF7DF88B" baseAuthorityName="Collin" baseAuthorityYear="1940" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pelecocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caledonica">
<emphasis id="78D38832961A456D5E32F938FF7DF88B" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="247">P. caledonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the length of the postocular orbits is dorsally, at the inner end of the eye, longer than a posterior ocellus); wing entirely covered in microtrichia (in 
<taxonomicName id="8DA72FA3961A456D59CBF8F8FBACF8AB" baseAuthorityName="Collin" baseAuthorityYear="1940" box="[907,1061,1826,1852]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pelecocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caledonica">
<emphasis id="78D38832961A456D59CBF8F8FBACF8AB" box="[907,1061,1826,1852]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="247">P. caledonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, basal medial (
<emphasis id="78D38832961B456C5AF8FA5CFF54FA36" box="[184,221,1415,1441]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">bm</emphasis>
) and posterior cubital cells (
<emphasis id="78D38832961B456C5872FA53FDD2FA36" box="[562,603,1416,1441]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">cup</emphasis>
) of the wing each with an area bare of microtrichia); tarsomeres 3+4 of fore and mid tarsi entirely pale, as well as the tibiae (
<figureCitation id="D29C48A5961B456C59B6FA7CFBCBFA56" box="[1014,1090,1447,1473]" captionStart="Figs 36–41" captionStartId="11.[174,213,1305,1327]" captionTargetBox="[204,1202,174,1283]" captionTargetId="figure-230@11.[204,1202,174,1283]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 36–41. Pelecocera (Chamaesyrphus) scaevoides: 36 — male habitus, dorsal view; 37 — male habitus, lateral view; 38 — male head and thorax, lateral view; 39 — male head, anterolateral view; 40 — male head, frontal view; 41 — female head, frontal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6455542" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6455542/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">fig. 37</figureCitation>
) (in 
<taxonomicName id="8DA72FA3961B456C5E3BFA73FF75FA76" baseAuthorityName="Collin" baseAuthorityYear="1940" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pelecocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caledonica">
<emphasis id="78D38832961B456C5E3BFA73FF75FA76" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">P. caledonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, tarsomeres 3+4 of fore and mid tarsi brown, darker than the tibiae); lunule with median triangle entirely, or partly, covered in dense, grey microtrichia (in 
<taxonomicName id="8DA72FA3961B456C5E6FFA33FB40F996" baseAuthorityName="Collin" baseAuthorityYear="1940" box="[1071,1225,1511,1537]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pelecocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caledonica">
<emphasis id="78D38832961B456C5E6FFA33FB40F996" box="[1071,1225,1511,1537]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">P. caledonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, lunule entirely undusted, brightly shining) (
<bibRefCitation id="2E3629D1961B456C58EFF9DCFC5AF9B6" author="Speight, M. C. D. &amp; Sarthou, J. - P." box="[687,979,1543,1569]" pageId="11" pageNumber="248" pagination="1 - 139" refId="ref12743" refString="Speight, M. C. D., Sarthou, J. - P. 2017. StN keys for the identification of the European species of various genera of Syrphidae 2017. Syrph the Net, the database of European Syrphidae (Diptera), 99, 1 - 139. Syrph the Net publications, Dublin." type="journal article" year="2017">Speight &amp; Sarthou, 2017</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="1ED804A8961B456C5AEEFAC2FD9CFAF3" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6455542" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6455542" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6455542/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="248" startId="11.[174,213,1305,1327]" targetBox="[204,1202,174,1283]" targetPageId="11">
<paragraph id="4A185420961B456C5AEEFAC2FD9CFAF3" blockId="11.[174,1232,1305,1380]" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">
Figs 36–41. 
<taxonomicName id="8DA72FA3961B456C5B60FAC2FD1FFAB9" baseAuthorityName="Fallen" baseAuthorityYear="1817" box="[288,662,1305,1327]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pelecocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scaevoides" subGenus="Chamaesyrphus">
