<paragraph id="4A185420961B456C5AA3F9FCFEEBF8D6" blockId="11.[174,1233,1415,1857]" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">
The 
<emphasis id="78D38832961B456C5B5BF9FCFEE4F9D6" bold="true" box="[283,365,1575,1601]" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">female</emphasis>
of 
<taxonomicName id="8DA72FA3961B456C5BDCF9FCFD1EF9D6" baseAuthorityName="Fallen" baseAuthorityYear="1817" box="[412,663,1575,1601]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pelecocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scaevoides">
<emphasis id="78D38832961B456C5BDCF9FCFD1EF9D6" box="[412,663,1575,1601]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">Pelecocera scaevoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="D29C48A5961B456C58EBF9FCFD72F9D6" box="[683,763,1575,1601]" captionStart="Figs 36–41" captionStartId="11.[174,213,1305,1327]" captionTargetBox="[204,1202,174,1283]" captionTargetId="figure-230@11.[204,1202,174,1283]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 36–41. Pelecocera (Chamaesyrphus) scaevoides: 36 — male habitus, dorsal view; 37 — male habitus, lateral view; 38 — male head and thorax, lateral view; 39 — male head, anterolateral view; 40 — male head, frontal view; 41 — female head, frontal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6455542" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6455542/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">fig. 41</figureCitation>
) can be separated from the female of 
<taxonomicName id="8DA72FA3961B456C5AEEF993FECEF9F6" baseAuthorityName="Collin" baseAuthorityYear="1940" box="[174,327,1607,1633]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pelecocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caledonica">
<emphasis id="78D38832961B456C5AEEF993FECEF9F6" box="[174,327,1607,1633]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">P. caledonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by: at the inner corner of the eye, on the dorsal surface of the head, the distance between the posterior margin of the eye and the posterior margin of the head is slightly greater than the length of a posterior ocellus, but distinctly less than 1.5x as long as a posterior ocellus (in 
<taxonomicName id="8DA72FA3961B456C5BF9F973FDDBF956" baseAuthorityName="Collin" baseAuthorityYear="1940" box="[441,594,1703,1729]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pelecocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caledonica">
<emphasis id="78D38832961B456C5BF9F973FDDBF956" box="[441,594,1703,1729]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">P. caledonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the distance between the posterior margin of the eye and the posterior margin of the head is slightly greater than 1.5x the length of a posterior ocellus); wing entirely covered in microtrichia (in 
<taxonomicName id="8DA72FA3961B456C5954F933FC26F896" baseAuthorityName="Collin" baseAuthorityYear="1940" box="[788,943,1767,1793]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pelecocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caledonica">
<emphasis id="78D38832961B456C5954F933FC26F896" box="[788,943,1767,1793]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">P. caledonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, basal medial (
<emphasis id="78D38832961B456C5E2AF93CFB06F896" box="[1130,1167,1767,1793]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">bm</emphasis>
) and posterior cubital cells (
<emphasis id="78D38832961B456C5BFBF8D3FE6DF8B6" box="[443,484,1800,1825]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">cup</emphasis>
) of the wing each with an area bare of microtrichia) (
<bibRefCitation id="2E3629D1961B456C5E1AF8DCFEDCF8D6" author="Speight, M. C. D. &amp; Sarthou, J. - P." pageId="11" pageNumber="248" pagination="1 - 139" refId="ref12743" refString="Speight, M. C. D., Sarthou, J. - P. 2017. StN keys for the identification of the European species of various genera of Syrphidae 2017. Syrph the Net, the database of European Syrphidae (Diptera), 99, 1 - 139. Syrph the Net publications, Dublin." type="journal article" year="2017">Speight &amp; Sarthou, 2017</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4A185420961C456B5A9BFF6BFC8EFF7E" blockId="12.[166,1224,175,234]" pageId="12" pageNumber="249">
Note. In 
<collectingCountry id="32B014B0961C456B5B0FFF74FE61FF5E" box="[335,488,175,201]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="12" pageNumber="249">Great Britain</collectingCountry>
this species is listed under the 
<collectingCountry id="32B014B0961C456B590AFF6BFCFAFF5D" box="[842,883,176,202]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="12" pageNumber="249">UK</collectingCountry>
Biodiversity Action Plan and qualified as Nationally Scarce (
<bibRefCitation id="2E3629D1961C456B584DFF14FD75FF7E" author="Ball, S. G. &amp; Morris, R. K. A." box="[525,764,207,233]" pageId="12" pageNumber="249" pagination="1 - 130" refId="ref10267" refString="Ball, S. G., Morris, R. K. A. 2014. A review of the scarce and threatened flies of Great Britain. Part 6: Syrphidae. Species status, No. 9, Joint Nature Conservation Committee, Peterborough, 1 - 130." type="book chapter" year="2014">Ball &amp; Morris, 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
